{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512782"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11952"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11952"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.08,0.23,0.33,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4548"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104451"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4548"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11952"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86778"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36551"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104451"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department complaining of sudden onset loss of vision in his right eye. He was sitting at home watching the television when he suddenly lost the upper half of his visual field in his right eye. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his pulse rate is 90/min and regular, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. ECG demonstrates sinus rhythm. Fundoscopic examination of his right eye is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is appropriate for his long term management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anticoagulation with apixaban","Optic nerve fenestration","Two weeks course of high dose oral prednisolone followed by a slow taper","Initiation of rosuvastatin therapy","Serial therapeutic lumbar punctures"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario and the picture above indicate a diagnosis of hemiretinal artery occlusion. At least two cholesterol emboli (known as Hollenhorst plaque)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eare visible. Commonly, emboli can not be visualised in cases of retinal artery occlusion however, rarely, the culprit emboli can be seen such as in this case. The cholesterol embolus appears as a discrete well demarcated yellow spot. In addition, the superiotemporal retina (on the left of the image) shows a retina that is pale in color in comparison to other parts of the retina. This suggests the presence of retinal edema that is secondary to the arterial occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute management of retinal artery occlusions is a point of contention with no evidence-based course of management yet showing a clear benefit. Multiple anecdotal practices are done in different centres. What is universally agreed upon is that the patient needs to undergo full systemic work up to assess cardiovascular risk factors. Any modifiable risk factor needs to be optimised to prevent another embolic episode to either eye or other arterial occlusive diseases such as MI or CVA. Though information is limited in this question, it is likely that a male patient in this age group has dyslipidaemia requiring treatment with a statin such as\u003Cstrong\u003E rosuvastatin.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntiplatelet therapy\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Emight be considered as part of treating cardiovascular risk factors with aspirin +/- clopidogrel, however \u003Cstrong\u003Eanticoagulation with apixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for this indication and would only be used in the setting of atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-dose oral or IV steroids\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered in cases where retinal artery occlusion is secondary to occlusive posterior uveitis or retinitis such as in Behcet disease. However, such patients typically present with decreased vision over many hours or days, frequently have bilateral involvement, and have other ocular and systemic signs and symptoms. In such cases, once an infection is ruled out or under control, high-dose steroids are used until a steroid-sparing or immune modifying agent is started.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic nerve fenestration \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E serial lumbar punctures \u003C/strong\u003Eare possible treatments in cases of benign intracranial hypertension (BIH) causing increased pressure on the optic nerve and secondary optic nerve compromise. They have no role in the management of arterial occlusive disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retinal artery occlusion secondary to cholesterol emboli is called Hollenhorst plaque.","Optimizing modifiable cardiovascular risk factors is paramount in decreasing the risk of future arterial occlusion in cases of retinal artery occlusion."],"references":["\u200cScot IU, Campochiaro PA, Newman NJ, et al. Retinal Vascular Occlusions. Lancet. 2020; 396: 1927\u201340."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86778"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11952"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16356"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16356","links":{"self":"https://a